Get involved
Volunteer: Outreach ambassador, driver, kit assembly, call‑banker, class aide, interpreter, pickleball coach/clinic helper
Donate: Fund care kits, groceries, transportation, teaching materials, and pickleball gear (paddles, balls, portable nets)
Partner: Shelters, clinics, senior centers, disability services, food banks, parks & recreation, schools, faith communities
Sign up: [Volunteer Form Link] [Donate Link] [Partner Interest Form Link]
Our approach
Community‑led: Promotores de salud and trusted grassroots partners guide our work
Culture‑centered: Bilingual communication and respect for traditions
Trauma‑informed: Safety, consent, privacy, and nonjudgmental support
Equity: No barriers based on income, immigration status, or documentation
Inclusive recreation: Adaptive coaching, warm‑ups, hydration breaks, shade/sunscreen, and safety guidelines at all clinics
Impact we track
Neighbors reached and care kits delivered
Seniors engaged through regular check‑ins and activities
Pounds of food distributed and deliveries completed
Class participation and skills gained
Pickleball clinics held, participants engaged, and gear distributed; number of new players continuing to play
Successful referrals to health, housing, and mental health services
Stories of resilience, movement, and community connection
Upcoming cadence
Week 1: Community food drive and pantry restock
Week 2: Senior circles and home visits
Week 3: Inclusive teaching workshops
Week 4: Homeless outreach and wellness corner pop‑up
Saturdays: Free pickleball clinics and open play (weather permitting)
Special events: Health fairs, resource days, caregiver trainings, and community pickleball days
FAQs
Who can participate? Anyone in our service area; priority for seniors, unhoused neighbors, people with disabilities, and cancer survivors
Is it free? Yes—services and clinics are provided at no cost
Do you offer mental health resources? Yes—education, support groups, and referrals to counseling and psycho‑oncology
Do you offer transportation? Limited assistance for medical and program appointments; ask about availability
How do I refer someone? Use the referral form or call [Phone Number]
Do I need pickleball gear or experience? No—gear is provided and coaches will teach basics; adaptive options available
Where are clinics held? Local parks and community centers; see [Link to calendar] for addresses and times
What about weather? We post day‑of updates on the calendar and social pages; indoor backup locations used when possible
